Beach Read by Emily Henry

A heartfelt contemporary romance about grief, healing and unexpected love by a summer lake.

January Andrews, reeling from grief and creative block, escapes to her late father’s lakeside cottage where she collides with her brooding neighbour Gus. As two writers confronting loss, identity, and buried emotion, they discover a connection that slowly deepens into love. The novel blends humour, emotional introspection, and romantic tension into a moving, character-driven story.

Audience Insights

BISAC Categories
Primary: Contemporary Romance
Secondary: Women's Fiction
Additional: Upmarket Fiction; Grief & Sudden Loss Fiction
Key Characteristics
The core readership consists of predominantly female adults aged 25–44 who seek emotionally resonant, character-driven fiction exploring grief, healing and intimate relationships. They favour romance with depth, authenticity and psychological nuance.

Analysis Overview

Readership
Classification
The book sits at the intersection of contemporary romance and upmarket women's fiction, offering emotional realism, grief exploration and literary-leaning introspection. It fits comfortably within small-town summer romances with psychological depth and occupies a competitive space alongside titles by Emily Henry, Christina Lauren, and Sally Rooney, distinguished by its bittersweet tone and authentic portrayal of creative and personal recovery.
Personas
Two clear personas emerge: Amelia, a creative, introspective millennial seeking emotional catharsis and authenticity; and Daniel, a mature, emotionally curious reader drawn to character-driven fiction that expands his emotional vocabulary. Both connect deeply with themes of grief, transformation, and slow-building romantic tension.
Marketing Guidance
Marketing should emphasise emotional healing, lakeside intimacy and a blend of humour and heartache. Position it as a summer read for fans of emotionally intelligent romance, using BookTok aesthetics, influencer-driven campaigns and strong character-led hooks. Emotional storytelling, grief-to-healing arcs and upmarket packaging will maximise reach across romance, women’s fiction and book club channels.

Mood and Tone

Bittersweet

Grief and healing run beneath the romantic arc, shaping the emotional texture and giving the narrative depth.

Reflective

The first-person voice blends introspection with humour as January processes loss, identity and creative block.

Romantic Tension

Slow-building chemistry between January and Gus creates emotional and narrative drive, balancing humour and vulnerability.

Hopeful

Despite the weight of grief, the story moves toward reconnection, growth and a believable, emotionally grounded future.

by Sally Rooney

by Linda Holmes

Similarities

  • • Themes of loss
  • • romantic connection post-trauma

Differences

  • • less dramatic character backstories

Deals with grief and emotional healing within a romantic framework set in a small town.

Market Gaps & Opportunities

Creating a hybrid space between character-driven women's fiction and commercial romance.

Readers increasingly demand romance with emotional weight and literary qualities.

Impact: Can differentiate the book in a crowded romance market and appeal wider through book clubs and crossover marketing.

Capitalize on BookTok and Instagram trends focusing on authenticity and emotional healing.

The book fits into prevailing micro-trends of ‘healing reads’ with emotionally relatable narratives.

Impact: Increased discoverability through organic user-generation and influencer marketing segments.

Cross-Genre Appeal with Contemporary Relevance

Uniquely positioned to bridge romantic escapism and emotional realism, offering readers both catharsis and connection.

Core Needs

Connection through shared experiences, inspiration to make a positive impact in her community, and stories that validate the importance of education and mentorship.

Fears

That the narrative will feel emotionally superficial or rely on clichés, lacking authenticity around grief and trauma.

Psychological Motivations

Emily seeks stories that highlight resilience, redemption, and community impact. As an educator, she resonates with narratives of mentorship and students overcoming challenges. She reads for emotional connection, inspiration, and a reminder that small acts can create meaningful change.

Value Drivers

Relatable characters, community-driven drama, emotionally uplifting arcs, and realistic yet hopeful resolutions.

Marketing Strategy

Pre-Launch

6 weeks pre-launch (awareness)

  • Introduce the title as an emotionally rich summer read that blends romance, grief and self-discovery for fans of Emily Henry and Christina Lauren.
  • Trailer videos, influencer unboxings, cover reveals, paid social ads, book community features
  • Amplify on-trend content formats tailored to BookTok (e.g., slow-burn romance, ‘books that healed me’), and segment creatives by sentiment.

Launch

2 weeks around launch (conversion)

  • Engage potential readers with samplers, author interviews, excerpt content and emotional reader reviews.
  • Instagram carousels, TikTok annotations, long-form email newsletters, author TikTok Q&As
  • Use A/B tested headlines focusing on healing/loss/love; feature choice quotes to evoke emotional connection.

Post-Launch

6 weeks post-launch (sustain momentum)

  • Drive pre-orders and purchases tied to emotional calls-to-action ideal for book clubs and individual readers.
  • Retailer-specific landing pages, discounts for early buyers, email reminders, retargeting social ads
  • Optimise timing during late spring/early summer, with location targeting for key physical events and UK retailer promotions.

Sample Copy

Back Cover Blurb

A secret lake house. A failing romance career. One complicated love interest. When January Andrews inherits her father’s lakeside cottage, she’s forced to confront his betrayals, her creative failures—and her growing feelings for her grumpy neighbour, Gus. Heartfelt, funny and emotionally raw, this is the romance you’ll carry with you long after the final page.

Video Creative Scripts

Script

Visuals open on a misty lakeside morning. Soft piano music plays. Voiceover: 'She thought she'd come to escape...' [Cut to January curled up reading, then gazing across the dock.] Voiceover: 'Instead she found someone who saw through her grief.' [Tease moments of laughter, soft touches, conflicted glances.] Voiceover: 'This summer, some endings become beginnings.' [Title reveal + CTA: Pre-order now.]

Sora Prompt

Create a slow, intimate video trailer featuring a young woman at a lakeside house in summer, with moments of laughter and reflection, visually highlighting romance, grief, and small-town life. Colour grade warm and soft.
